      "content": "i get that, but it feels like you're saying the benefits of the policy automatically outweigh any harm to people's wallets. if the policy ends up hurting the very people it claims to help—like small business owners in the outer boroughs or people who literally can't afford a car and have no other choice—isn't that then inherently an unfair or even regressive policy? how can you call it a \"solution\" if it creates that kind of inequality?",
